Preliminary analysis of particle placement experiment

Jason Grafmiller

12 January, 2021

This is a quick preliminary analysis of the results from out particle placement 100-split rating task experiments.

Quick Summary

  • We find a significant positive correlation between corpus model predictions and experimental ratings.
  • We find a significant main effect of Direct Object length on the experimental ratings. The split variant is disfavored as the direct object gets longer, just as in the corpus model.
  • We find a significant main effect of Country. IN participants tend to prefer the continuous variant slightly more than the GB participants.
  • No interaction effects of Country and either Dir Obj length or Corpus predictions
  • A few verbs show large differences in mean preferences between IN and GB participants, but for most verbs participants’ constructional preferences generally agree.

Visualizing the data

Corpus predictions vs. ratings in aggregate

First we can look at the correlations between the predicted log odds from the corpus model and the mean ratings by verb. We can consider different smoothers, to see whether there is any nonlinearity that we should account for. The plot below shows that there clearly is a correlation.

Now if we average over the individual verbs in the stimuli, we can see a little better

The relationship appears to be surprisingly (to me at least) linear. There’s not much curvature in the GAM smoother, so we may be able to get away with a simple linear model. It may also be worth looking at the two cases with extremely low corpus model predictions: carry out and rule out. Why do these tokens have such low predicted probabilities?

If we separate the ratings Country (with GAM smooths), the pattern really doesn’t change much.

Standardizing doesn’t change the distribution of the response, only the scale, nor does transforming the ratings to the logit scale.

Lexical patterns

Do the GB and IN participants rate verbs the same way? It’s worth looking at the individual items and seeing where the different groups diverge.

From the plot, it seems that for most verbs, the IN participants favor the joined/continuous variant more than the GB participants. In most cases the differences are not large, but for a few verbs (put in, get in, bring down) there is a substantial difference between the IN and GB participants on the order of 20-30 points or more.

We can also inspect the full distributions of the ratings for each verb across all participants. It’s clear that there are some verbs/tokens that everyone seems to agree on, e.g. give up and keep down, and others for which there is less agreement (those near the middle of the plot , e.g. put away and drive away).

Patterns across individuals

Models

Below I consider some alternative models for the data. One question was whether we should use GAM(M)s or simple linear models. Based on the visual inspection above and the results from preliminary GAMM models in the next section, I think a simpler linear model is justified for these data. In the second section I run some Bayesian linear models.

Linear or GAMM models?

First we’ll consider whether we want to use a simpler linear model, or a more complex generalized additive model (GAM).

Linear mixed model

So here is a simple linear mixed-model of the ratings, with only random intercepts for item and participant. Barr et al. (2013) of course suggest that maximal random structure should be used, but this “maximalist” approach has been critiqued (Bates et al. 2015; Matuschek et al. 2017), so we should examine the random structure a bit to see what is justified. But for now, I’m keeping it simple.

summary(lmer1 <- lmer(
  rating_st ~ (1|item) + (1|id) + z.DirObjWordLength * condition + pred_min, 
  data = rats2
  ))

Type II Wald tests suggest that condition and z.DirObjWordLength have significant effects, but there is no interaction effect.

The effects plot illustrates the weak effect of DO length, such that as the DO gets longer, participants tend to favor the joined variant more, and it shows that British participants do tend to like the split variant slightly more than Indian participants. This difference by country holds regardless of DO length. There is a clear effect of model predictions.

Now we check the model fit quickly using the really helpful performance package.

model_performance(lmer1) %>% round(3)

Not too good… The low marginal \(R^2\) tells us that the fixed effects predictors aren’t that doing much. We can also look at the model diagnostics and see if we have any reason to worry.

check_model(lmer1)

I don’t know… Mostly looks good, but there is a good deal of heteroskedasticity, which could be concerning. I’ll set that aside for now.

GAMM model

Fit a GAMM with mgcv. Since there are only 6 unique values for z.DirObjWordLength, we’ll set the knots to 3.

Indian participants tend to prefer the continuous variation significantly more than GB participants, which is interesting. But this is only a small effect: only a difference of .17 standard deviations, which is about 6-7 points on our rating scale if my calculations are correct. There is some curvature in the z.DirObjWordLength, but not much. We could maybe leave this smoothing term out.

If we look at the smoothing terms, things go in the expected direction, with some wiggliness. Not sure whether we need to say much about this here.
